**Page 1 — Section opener**

### What AI Actually Is

Before we go any further, we need to clear up what we're actually talking about when we say "AI". The term gets used so loosely it's basically meaningless. People use it to mean ChatGPT, the recommendation algorithm on TikTok, the autopilot on a Tesla, and the spam filter on Gmail. All of those are technically AI. None of them are the same thing.

By the end of this section you'll understand:

- The difference between AI and AGI (and why the difference matters)
- How AI, machine learning, deep learning and generative AI all fit together
- What an LLM actually is and how it works
- What tokens and context windows are
- The difference between closed and open-source AI models

Some of this is a bit dense. Take it in chunks if you need to. The good news is that once you've got the basic concepts, the rest of the guide is mostly about applying them.

---

**Page 2 — AI vs. AGI**

You'll hear two terms thrown around: AI and AGI. They're related but they mean different things.

**AI (Artificial Intelligence)** is what we have now. It's the broad field of building systems that can do things we'd normally need a human brain to do — recognising images, understanding language, making predictions, generating text. AI is everywhere already: your bank's fraud detection, your phone's voice assistant, the chatbot on a delivery company's website, the tool that auto-edits your photos.

The key thing about today's AI is that it's *narrow*. Each system is built for a specific task and can only do that task. ChatGPT is brilliant at language but couldn't drive a car. A self-driving system can navigate a motorway but can't write you an email. They're specialists, not generalists.

**AGI (Artificial General Intelligence)** is the theoretical version that doesn't exist yet — a system that can do any intellectual task a human can do, across any domain, without being specifically trained for it. AGI would be able to read a contract, then plan a meal, then debug your code, then understand your kid's homework, all using the same underlying intelligence. The goal of the big companies like OpenAI is to create AGI, and they’re basically in a massive arms race as to who can do it first.

Whether AGI is months away, decades away, or never going to happen depends entirely on who you ask. Some serious researchers think we're close. Others think the current path won't get us there. For the purposes of running a business, AGI doesn't really matter yet — you're going to be working with narrow AI tools for the foreseeable future. But it's worth knowing the term exists, because you'll see it used a lot.

For the rest of this guide, when we say "AI" we mean what's available today: narrow, specialised, but increasingly capable.

---

**Page 3 — How it all fits together**

Here's the bit that confuses most people. There are four terms you'll hear constantly — AI, machine learning, deep learning, and generative AI — and they all sound similar but mean different things. They're not separate technologies. They're nested inside each other.

**[Visual 1 — nested rings diagram sits here]**

Working from the outside in:

**Artificial Intelligence** is the broadest term. It covers any attempt to make a computer do something that would normally require human intelligence. This goes back to the 1950s — long before anyone was talking about ChatGPT. Old-school AI included things like chess-playing programs and expert systems used in medicine and engineering. None of it was particularly clever by today's standards, but it was AI.

**Machine Learning** is a subset of AI. Instead of programming a computer with explicit rules ("if this happens, do that"), you give it large amounts of data and let it figure out the patterns itself. This is what powers Netflix recommendations, fraud detection on your credit card, and the spam filter in your inbox. The system learns from examples rather than being told what to do.

**Deep Learning** is a subset of machine learning. It uses something called *neural networks* — software designed to loosely mimic how the human brain processes information, with multiple layers stacked on top of each other. This is where AI started getting genuinely impressive, around the early 2010s. Image recognition that could identify cats in photos. Translation tools that worked properly for the first time. Voice assistants that could actually understand you.

**Generative AI** is a subset of deep learning. This is the one that's blown up in the last three years. Instead of just classifying or predicting things, generative AI *creates* things — text, images, video, audio, code. ChatGPT, Claude, Midjourney, and the AI features showing up in every piece of software are all generative AI.

When most people today say "AI", they usually mean generative AI specifically. That's what we'll mostly focus on in the rest of this guide, because it's the bit that matters for small business owners right now.

---

**Page 4 — LLMs are prediction machines**

This is the single most important concept in the guide. If you take one thing from this section, take this.

**Large Language Models — the technology behind ChatGPT, Claude, and most AI chat tools — are prediction machines.** That's it. That's what they do.

When you type a question into ChatGPT, it doesn't "understand" your question the way a human does. It doesn't think about it. It doesn't know things in the way you know things. What it does is predict what words should come next, given the words that came before. It does that one word (or one *token* — more on this in a minute) at a time, until it's generated a complete response.

The closest everyday comparison is the autocomplete on your phone.

**[Visual 2 — autocomplete vs LLM comparison sits here]**

When you start typing "I'll be home for" on your phone, it suggests "dinner" or "lunch" or "Christmas" because those are statistically the most likely words to come next, based on patterns it's learned from millions of other text messages.

An LLM is doing the same thing — predicting the most likely next word based on patterns — but at a much bigger scale, with vastly more training data, and capable of predicting whole paragraphs of coherent text rather than just the next single word.

This sounds underwhelming when you put it like that. *"It's just predicting the next word? How is that doing all the impressive stuff I've seen?"*

The answer is: turns out, if you predict next words really, really well — based on having read most of the text on the internet — you can do a surprising amount of useful things. You can write a coherent email. You can summarise a long document. You can explain a complex topic. You can suggest improvements to a business plan. Not because the AI understands any of it, but because it's seen enough examples of good emails, summaries, explanations, and business plans that it can produce convincing new ones.

**Why this matters practically.** Once you understand that LLMs are prediction machines, three things become obvious:

1. **They can be wrong, confidently.** They predict what's *likely* to come next, not what's *true*. If they've seen lots of text that says something incorrect, they'll predict that incorrect thing back to you with total confidence. This is called "hallucination" and it's covered properly in Section 7.
2. **They can't read your mind.** They only have what you give them in the prompt to work with. The more context you provide, the better their predictions get. Vague prompts produce vague answers. This is why prompt quality matters so much, which is covered in detail in Guide 2.
3. **They don't actually "know" things.** They've absorbed patterns from training data. There's no internal database of facts they're looking things up in. Which is why they sometimes get basic facts wrong — they're predicting plausible-sounding answers, not retrieving verified information.

Keep this in mind for the rest of the guide. Everything else builds on it.

