**Page 5 — Tokens, context windows, and training data**

A few more concepts you'll bump into.

**Tokens.** LLMs don't read words the way you do. They break text up into smaller chunks called tokens. A token is usually somewhere between half a word and a full word — common words might be one token, longer or unusual words get split into pieces.

**[Visual 3 — token breakdown sits here]**

You don't need to think about tokens day-to-day. But it's useful to know they exist, because:

- AI tools usually charge based on tokens used (input + output)
- Every model has a limit on how many tokens it can handle in one conversation — this is called the **context window**
- Long, rambling prompts use more tokens than tight, focused ones

**Context window.** This is the maximum amount of text an AI can hold in its "working memory" at once — your prompt plus its response, plus any documents you've pasted in, plus the conversation so far. Different models have different sizes. Claude can handle hundreds of thousands of tokens at once. ChatGPT's free tier is more limited.

When you exceed the context window — usually by having a very long conversation or pasting in massive documents — the AI starts forgetting the earliest parts. This is sometimes called *context rot*, and it's why long chat threads gradually get worse. We'll come back to this in Section 7.

**Training data.** This is the data the model learned from. For the big LLMs, that means roughly: most of the public internet, large numbers of books, Wikipedia, scientific papers, code repositories, and various other text sources. Hundreds of billions of words.

This is worth understanding because it explains a few things about how LLMs behave:

- **They're frozen at a particular date.** Models have a "training cutoff" — they don't know about events after a certain point unless they're specifically given access to web search.
- **They reflect the biases of their training data.** If most of the internet writes about a topic in a particular way, the model will too. This isn't always good.
- **They don't have access to your business's data unless you give it to them.** A fresh ChatGPT session knows nothing about your customers, your pricing, your operations. You have to provide that context.

The "data is just data" idea is worth pausing on. People sometimes treat AI like it's magic, but underneath it's just very large amounts of text being processed in clever ways. The quality of an AI's outputs is constrained by what it was trained on and what you give it to work with. There's no oracle in there. Just a really powerful pattern-matcher.

