**Page 6 — Closed vs. open-source models**

One last distinction worth knowing about: closed source vs. open source AI.

**[Visual 4 — comparison table sits here]**

**Closed source models** are owned and controlled by the company that built them. You can use them, but only through their interfaces or APIs. You can't see how they work internally, you can't run them on your own computer, and you can't modify them. Examples: ChatGPT (OpenAI), Claude (Anthropic), Gemini (Google), Grok (xAI).

**Open source models** are released publicly. The code and the model itself are available for anyone to download, run, modify, and build on. Examples: Llama (Meta), DeepSeek, Mistral, and various others.

For most small businesses, this distinction doesn't matter much in day-to-day use. You'll probably use closed-source models like Claude or ChatGPT through their normal interfaces because they're the most capable and the easiest to use.

Where it does start to matter:

- **Data privacy.** When you use a closed model through its standard interface, your data is sent to the company's servers. They have policies about what they do with it (worth reading), but the data leaves your control. With open source models, you can theoretically run them on your own hardware and keep all data in-house.
- **Cost at scale.** If you're using AI heavily across your business, closed-model API costs can add up. Open source models can be cheaper to run at scale, though they require technical setup.
- **Customisation.** Open source models can be modified and fine-tuned for specific use cases. Closed models can't.

**A note on self-hosting.** "Self-hosting" means running an AI model on your own computer or your own servers, rather than using someone else's cloud service. This is technically possible with open source models. For most small businesses it's overkill — the setup, hardware, and maintenance aren't worth the hassle. But if you handle highly sensitive data (legal, medical, financial), it's an option worth knowing exists. If that applies to you, get someone technical involved.

---

**Page 7 — Section recap**

That was a lot. Here's the short version of what to remember:

- **AI** is a broad term covering any attempt to make computers do "intelligent" things. **AGI** is the theoretical version that can do everything a human can. We're nowhere near AGI.
- **Machine learning, deep learning, and generative AI** are nested inside each other, like Russian dolls. Generative AI is the bit causing all the recent fuss.
- **LLMs are prediction machines.** They predict what comes next based on patterns. They're not thinking, understanding, or knowing — they're predicting. This explains most of their strengths and most of their weaknesses.
- **Tokens** are how AI reads and writes text. **Context windows** are how much they can hold in working memory at once. Bigger is better.
- **Training data** is what they learned from. They're frozen at a point in time and don't know your business unless you tell them.
- **Closed vs. open source.** For most small businesses, you'll be using closed source models like Claude or ChatGPT. Open source matters for privacy, cost at scale, and customisation.

That's the foundation. Next, we'll look at the actual tools available — what they're called, what they're for, and how to think about which ones to pay attention to.

