### Page 5 — The Sora story (and why you shouldn't marry a tool)

Worth telling this one in full because it makes a point better than any abstract advice could.

In February 2024, OpenAI announced Sora, an AI video generation model. The demos were stunning — cinematic clips of waves crashing, characters walking through Tokyo streets, all generated from a single text prompt. The hype was enormous. Disney was reportedly planning a $1 billion investment in OpenAI partly off the back of Sora.

Sora launched publicly in December 2024. Subscriptions started at $20 a month. By January 2026, it had over 4 million active users.

In March 2026, OpenAI shut it down.

**[Visual 2 — Sora timeline sits here]**

The reasons were essentially economic. Running Sora was expensive — reportedly $8–12 million a month in compute costs against $2 million in revenue. OpenAI decided the resources were better spent on their core products. The tool that millions of people had built workflows around was switched off, with weeks of notice.

This isn't a story about Sora being a bad product. It's a story about what happens when you build your business around a single tool from a single company. The same thing could happen tomorrow to Midjourney, to Claude, to any of them. Companies pivot. Pricing changes. Products get shut down.

The lesson for any small business using AI: **understand the principles, not just the tools.** If you understand what AI is doing and why, switching from one tool to another when you need to is a minor inconvenience. If you've built your entire workflow around a specific product and don't really understand how it works, you're vulnerable to that product changing or disappearing.

This is one of the things we're trying to do with this guide — give you enough understanding that you're not dependent on any one tool. The tools will keep changing. The underlying principles won't.

