### Page 6 — Why "AI" is suddenly in everything (and why most of it is rubbish)

Walk through any software company's marketing in 2026 and you'll struggle to find a product that doesn't claim to be "AI-powered" or have "AI features built in". Photoshop has AI. Notion has AI. Your accounting software has AI. The app you use to book restaurant tables probably has AI now too.

Some of this is genuine and useful. Most of it isn't.

**[Visual 3 — "AI in everything" parody sits here]**

The pattern is depressingly consistent. A company that's been struggling to compete suddenly slaps "AI" on every feature in its product. Existing features get renamed — "Smart Search" becomes "AI-Powered Search". A chatbot gets bolted onto the corner of the interface. Marketing pages suddenly talk about how the product is "leveraging artificial intelligence to transform your workflow". And usually, none of it actually makes the product better. Often it makes it worse — slower, more confusing, or just adding a layer of noise the user has to navigate around.

The cynical version: many companies are using "AI" the same way they used to use "cloud" or "blockchain" — as a buzzword to attract attention and justify higher prices. The genuine version: they're under pressure from investors and customers to "do something with AI", and shipping half-baked features is easier than thinking carefully about where AI actually adds value.

**The exceptions are worth pointing out.** Adobe's Firefly, integrated into Photoshop and the rest of the Adobe suite, is a genuinely useful AI feature embedded in an existing tool — it speeds up real tasks designers were already doing. Microsoft Copilot inside Office 365 has real use cases for businesses that already work in Word and Excel. Where AI is added thoughtfully to a tool people already use for real work, it can be excellent.

Where it's added as marketing decoration, it's worse than useless.

**This is one of the things we care about at Kelvinstone.** When we build automations or AI-powered workflows for clients, the test is always: *does this actually save time and reduce work?* If it doesn't, it doesn't go in. There's enough genuine value to be had from AI that there's no need to dress up half-measures. The point of automation is to remove friction, not add a new layer of it.

When you're evaluating any tool that claims AI features, ask yourself: *is this making my actual job easier, or is this just AI for the sake of saying you have AI?* If you can't answer that clearly, the AI features probably aren't worth paying extra for.

