### Page 1 — Section opener

### Deterministic Automation vs. AI Automation

Here's something almost nobody tells you: not every problem needs AI.

The AI hype machine has spent the last three years convincing everyone that AI is the answer to every business problem. It isn't. A lot of what makes a small business inefficient can be solved with much simpler tools — automation that's been around for a decade and that costs almost nothing to set up.

This section covers the difference between two types of automation, when each one is the right call, and how they fit together in real workflows. By the end you'll know:

- The difference between deterministic automation and AI automation
- When to use which (and when to use both)
- How any automation is structured at a basic level
- Why the most useful systems usually combine the two

This is the section that separates people who can think clearly about automation from people who just throw "AI" at every problem and hope for the best.

---

### Page 2 — Two different kinds of automation

**Deterministic automation** is the old school. It's been around since the 2010s, and it's what most small businesses already touch in some form, even if they don't realise it.

The principle is simple: *if this happens, do that.* A form gets filled out → save the data to a spreadsheet. An invoice gets paid → send a thank you email. A new customer signs up → add them to a mailing list. The system follows a fixed set of rules. There's no thinking involved. It just does what it's told, exactly the same way, every time.

The big advantages: it's cheap, it's reliable, it's predictable, and it doesn't make mistakes. Once it's set up properly, it just runs.

The big limitation: it can't handle anything that requires interpretation. If the situation doesn't match the rules exactly, it either does nothing or does the wrong thing.

**AI automation** is the newer category. It uses an AI model — a large language model like Claude or ChatGPT — as part of the workflow to handle the bits that need judgment.

A customer enquiry comes in. Is it a qualified lead, or is it spam? Is the person asking about a service you offer, or about something completely different? Should this be answered immediately or routed to someone for review? An LLM can read the enquiry and make those calls in a way that deterministic automation simply can't. It doesn't follow a rigid rule — it interprets, decides, and responds.

The big advantage: AI handles the messy, language-based, judgment-requiring parts of business that used to need a human.

The big limitations: it costs more (every AI call uses tokens, which cost money), it's slower (a few seconds per step instead of milliseconds), and it's not always perfectly consistent (the same input might produce slightly different outputs).

**[Visual 1 — decision tree sits here]**

The right question isn't *"deterministic or AI?"* It's *"which parts of this workflow need judgment, and which parts don't?"* Use AI only for the parts that genuinely need it. Use deterministic automation for everything else. You'll save money, you'll get more reliable systems, and the AI parts will work better because they're focused on what they're actually good at.

---

### Page 3 — The basic shape of any workflow

Whether a workflow uses AI or not, every automation has the same basic structure. Three parts.

**[Visual 2 — trigger / logic / outcome diagram sits here]**

**The trigger** is what starts the workflow. Something happens, and the system kicks into action. A form gets submitted. An email arrives. A payment lands. The clock hits 9am. A new file gets uploaded to a folder. Without a trigger, nothing happens.

**The logic** is the middle bit — what the system actually does once it's been triggered. This is where the work gets done. Deterministic logic is rules: *if the email is from a known customer, file it under their name*. AI logic is judgment: *read the email and decide whether it needs an urgent reply*. Most workflows have several logic steps chained together.

**The outcome** is what comes out the other end. A useful thing happens in the world. A WhatsApp message gets sent to the owner. A calendar event gets created. A document gets saved. An invoice gets drafted. The whole point of the workflow is to produce this outcome without anyone having to do it manually.

That's it. Trigger → logic → outcome. Every automation, AI-powered or not, follows this pattern. Once you see it, you start spotting opportunities for automation everywhere in your business — anywhere you've got a repetitive *"every time X happens, I have to do Y"* situation, you've got a candidate for a workflow.

---

### Page 4 — A worked example

Let's walk through a real workflow that combines deterministic and AI automation, so you can see how they fit together.

The scenario: a small business gets enquiries through a contact form on their website. Right now, the owner manually checks the form submissions, decides which ones are worth following up, and writes a reply to each one. It takes 30–45 minutes a day and means new leads sometimes wait 24 hours for a response.

Here's what an automated version of this might look like:

**[Visual 3 — worked example walkthrough sits here]**

A few things to notice about this workflow:

- **The trigger is deterministic.** Form submission happens, automation starts. No AI needed for that.
- **Saving the submission to a spreadsheet is deterministic.** It's just copying data from one place to another. Using AI for that would be a waste of money and add latency for no reason.
- **Qualifying the enquiry uses AI.** This is the part that requires judgment. An LLM can read "Hi, do you do bathroom installations in Glasgow?" and recognise it as a real lead, while flagging "CHEAP SEO SERVICES CLICK HERE" as spam. Deterministic rules struggle with this — you'd need to write hundreds of conditions and you'd still miss things.
- **Drafting the reply uses AI.** Personalised, contextual responses are exactly what LLMs are good at. The AI doesn't send the reply — it suggests one.
- **Sending the WhatsApp notification is deterministic.** Once the AI has done its work, getting the result to the owner is just plumbing.
- **The human is still in the loop.** The owner sees the enquiry and the suggested reply, makes any tweaks, and sends. The system saves them time without taking them out of the relationship.

This is what good AI automation looks like. AI is used surgically, only where it adds value. The boring parts stay boring (and cheap, and reliable). The human stays in control of anything that touches the customer directly.

The owner has gone from spending 30–45 minutes a day on enquiries to spending 5 minutes reviewing pre-drafted replies. And new leads get a response within minutes instead of hours, which makes a real difference to conversion.

