### Page 5 — The tools that let you build this

You don't need to be a developer to build workflows like the one on the previous page. There's a whole category of tools called **workflow builders** (or "no-code automation platforms") that let you connect different apps and services together visually.

The big names you'll encounter:

**Zapier** is the easiest to start with. It's been around the longest, has the biggest library of integrations (it connects to thousands of different apps), and you can build basic workflows in minutes. The trade-off is that it gets expensive fast as you add more workflows or more steps. Best for simple automations and people who've never touched this stuff before.

**Make** (formerly called Integromat) is a step up in complexity and capability. Better at handling complex, multi-step workflows. More flexible than Zapier. The interface takes a bit longer to learn but you get more power for your money.

**n8n** is what we use at Kelvinstone for most of our client work. It's open source, much cheaper than the alternatives at scale, and gives you the most flexibility for complex workflows. The trade-off is it's the most technical of the three. Not something most small business owners would set up themselves, but worth knowing the name.

For most small businesses thinking about this for the first time, the right path is either:

- **Try Zapier yourself** for simple things (notifications, basic data routing, "when X happens, do Y" stuff)
- **Get someone else to build it** if you want anything more complex than that — particularly anything involving AI

The reason to bring someone in for the AI stuff isn't because it's hard to do badly. It's because it's hard to do well. Setting up a workflow that "uses AI" is easy. Setting up one that uses AI in the right places, doesn't waste tokens, doesn't break in unexpected ways, and actually saves you time rather than creating new problems — that takes more thought.

This is most of what we do at Kelvinstone, for what it's worth. But the principles in this guide apply whether you build the systems yourself, hire us, or hire someone else.

