### Page 2 — The six categories

Across thousands of small businesses adopting AI, the same six categories keep showing up. Not because they're the most exciting — because they're the most *frequent*. The tasks eating 30 minutes here, an hour there, across every working day.

**[Visual 1 — six categories grid sits here]**

**1. Enquiry handling and lead qualification.** When a customer fills out a form, sends an email, or messages you on social media, AI can read it, decide whether it's a real lead or noise, draft a personalised first reply, and route it to you with the relevant context. According to multiple 2026 surveys this is consistently the highest-ROI entry point for small businesses — partly because it sits closest to revenue, partly because nobody enjoys doing it manually.

**2. Appointment scheduling.** Booking, rescheduling, sending reminders, chasing no-shows. The deterministic parts of this (calendar slots, automated reminders) have been around for a decade. What's new is AI handling the conversational parts — a customer messaging "any chance you could come Tuesday afternoon?" and the system understanding the request, checking availability, and proposing options.

**3. Follow-ups and customer communication.** The post-job thank you, the payment reminder, the review request a week after a job, the check-in two months later. Most small businesses know they should do these things consistently. Most don't, because they're tedious and easy to forget. AI removes the "remembering" part of the equation, and drafts the messages for you.

**4. Content creation.** We’ve all been drilled with the fact that social media is so important these days. Online presence is everything, and is crucial for your lead generation. Drafting social media posts, marketing emails, blog content, website quality and copy. According to Salesforce, marketing and customer engagement are the top priority areas for AI among 77% of small businesses [AdAI](https://adai.news/resources/statistics/small-business-ai-statistics-2026/) — and content creation is the most common use case, full stop. The reason it tops the list: the ROI is immediately obvious. A task that took 4 hours now takes under 1 hour.

**5. Admin and documentation.** Invoice processing, expense categorisation, meeting notes, basic reports, document classification. Public case studies show targeted automation can cut manual invoice processing time by up to 80% [Distrya](https://distrya.com/blog/ai-adoption-for-small-business-2026-roi-focused-roadmap). Less glamorous than content creation, but often delivers bigger time savings because the work is so repetitive.

**6. Internal knowledge and FAQs.** Answering the same customer questions over and over — pricing, availability, service areas, policies. AI can handle the first layer of this automatically, only escalating to you when something genuinely new comes up. For service businesses with high enquiry volume this is one of the highest-impact automations available.

A few things worth noticing about this list. None of these are exotic. None of them require you to fundamentally change how your business works. They're all variations on "the boring repetitive bits, done faster and more consistently." That's what good AI automation looks like in 2026 — not science fiction, just removing friction from work you already do.

