### Page 3 — The "broken down into instructions" test

Here's the most useful test for spotting automation opportunities in your own business.

**If you can describe how you'd train a new employee to do the task, it's probably a candidate for automation.**

Think about it. Training someone to do a task means you can articulate:

- When the task starts (the trigger)
- What inputs you have (the information available)
- What steps you take (the logic)
- What the final output looks like (the outcome)

If you can do all of that, you've essentially written the spec for an automation. It might still need AI for the judgment-heavy parts (Section 5), but the structure is there. You've already proven the task can be broken down into instructions.

The reverse is also useful. If you *can't* describe how you'd train someone else to do something — if it relies entirely on your specific intuition, your relationships, your taste, your physical presence — then it's probably not a good automation candidate. Don't try to force it.

**[Visual 2 — broken down into instructions comparison sits here]**

A useful nuance for service businesses, especially trades: **the field work isn't what gets automated. The back-office work supporting the field work is.** The plumber doing the actual job, building trust at the door, diagnosing the unusual fault — that stays human. But the enquiry that came in last night, the booking confirmation, the payment reminder, the review request afterwards — all of that is fair game.

This is actually one of the more interesting findings of the last two years of AI adoption: in many service businesses, the field workers are safer than the office staff supporting them. Dispatching, scheduling, basic customer service, and administrative work are being automated rapidly, while the field work itself remains entirely human [Thebluecollarrecruiter](https://thebluecollarrecruiter.com/ai-vs-skilled-trades-in-2026-whats-actually-threatened-and-what-isnt/). The implication for small business owners: AI doesn't threaten the part of your business that actually creates value. It threatens the friction layer around it — and getting rid of friction is a good thing.

