### Page 4 — Data privacy

This is one of the things that genuinely matters and that most small business owners don't think about until they should have done.

When you type something into ChatGPT, Claude, or any other AI tool, that text leaves your computer and goes to the company's servers. They process it, generate a response, and send the response back. Depending on the tool and the plan you're on, they may also store your conversations and use them to train future models.

For asking general questions — *"explain X to me"*, *"draft a generic email"*, *"summarise this article"* — this is fine. Nothing sensitive is leaving your control.

For business data, it's worth thinking carefully.

**[Visual 3 — privacy decision tree sits here]**

A few rules of thumb:

**On free / personal tiers, assume your data may be used for training.** OpenAI, Anthropic, and Google all have different policies, and they change. Free tiers generally have weaker privacy protections than paid ones. If you're going to share anything sensitive, use a paid plan and read the privacy policy.

**Business and Enterprise tiers usually offer stronger guarantees.** ChatGPT Team/Enterprise, Claude for Work, Gemini Workspace — these typically include a "we won't train on your data" clause and stronger security guarantees. If you're using AI for client work, this is worth the upgrade.

**Some data shouldn't go into AI tools at all.** Anything you have a legal duty to protect (financial records, medical details, anything covered by GDPR, anything covered by client confidentiality agreements) needs careful handling. The default assumption should be: don't paste it into ChatGPT unless you've checked the privacy implications.

**For genuinely sensitive use cases, self-hosted models exist.** As covered in Section 3, open-source models like Llama and DeepSeek can be run on your own hardware, which means data never leaves your control. This is overkill for most small businesses, but it's an option for legal, medical, or financial work where the stakes are high.

The simple version: when in doubt, leave it out. There's almost always a way to get value from AI without putting your most sensitive data through it. Use anonymised examples. Use templates instead of real client emails. Keep the most sensitive bits offline.

